04771nam a22007215i 9789633863541DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222009hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338635417 a10.1515/97896338635412doi  a(DE-B1597)633201  a(OCoLC)1338020154  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aD802.L5bD313 2009eb 7aBIO0080002bisacsh04a940.53/47930922221 aLuksa, Juozas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForest Brothers :bThe Account of an Anti-Soviet Lithuanian Freedom Fighter, 1944–1948 /cJuozas Luksa. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (422 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Invisible Front: Lithuania’s Armed Resistance Against the Soviet Union -- tPart I. The Decision to Stay on our Native Land, July 1944–July 1945 -- tBetween Home and Kaunas -- tThe Armed Resistance -- tPart II. Choosing the Fate of a Partisan, July 1945–January 1946 -- tThere Was No Other Choice -- tPart III. On the Partisan Road, January 1946–May 1947 -- tTaking My First Steps as a Partisan -- tTaking on a Position of Leadership -- tPart IV. Breaking Through the Iron Curtain to the West, June 1947–December 1947 -- tThe First Journey -- tThe West Recommends We Return and Wait -- tAfterword -- tA Journey into the Heart: A Post-War Love Story -- tAn Account from the Post-War Borderlands -- tAppendix0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn autobiographical account of the armed resistance against the Soviet Union, which took place between 1944–1956. Published in English for the first time in unabridged form, Lukša's memoir remains one of the few reliable eye-witness accounts of the "Invisible Front", as dubbed by Soviet security forces. At its zenith 28,000 guerilla fighters participated in battles and skirmishes throughout Lithuania, Lukša (partisan codename Daumantas) being one of the leaders. Forest Brothers also documents the role of women in the resistance, giving equal credit to these often silent partners. In 1948 Lukša and two comrades broke through the Iron Curtain on the Polish border. He sought training from the French intelligence and from the CIA. Lukša was flown back into the Soviet Union under the radar on the night of October 4, 1950. He managed to survive and operate eleven months until his near capture and death on the night of September 5, 1951. His account, written during 1948–1950, while he was living in hiding in Paris, describes in vivid scenes and dialogue the daily struggles of the resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aGuerrillaszLithuaniavBiography. 0aInsurgencyzLithuaniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Lithuanian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xUnderground movementszLithuania. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Military.2bisacsh  aCommunism, Insurgency, Memoir, Personal narratives, Political violence, World War II.1 aVincė, Laima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aÖhman, Jonas Ö, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386354140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633863541423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633863541/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SS